# Command woodpecker-cli

## What does this command do:

woodpecker-cli - command line utility. Works with woodpecker CI

## Installed from

For Fedora install using:
```
curl -L https://github.com/woodpecker-ci/woodpecker/releases/download/v3.13.0/woodpecker-cli_linux_amd64.tar.gz \
  | tar xz -C /tmp
sudo mv /tmp/woodpecker-cli /usr/local/bin/
```

For Raspberry Pi install using:
```
curl -L https://github.com/woodpecker-ci/woodpecker/releases/download/v3.13.0/woodpecker-cli_linux_arm64.tar.gz \
  | tar xz -C /tmp
sudo mv /tmp/woodpecker-cli /usr/local/bin/
```

For Mac install using:
```
curl -L https://github.com/woodpecker-ci/woodpecker/releases/download/v3.13.0/woodpecker-cli_darwin_arm64.tar.gz \
  | tar xz -C /tmp
mv /tmp/woodpecker-cli ~/.local/bin/
```

## Command path

For Fedora run: woodpecker-cli
For Raspberry Pi run: woodpecker-cli
For Mac run: ~/.local/bin/woodpecker-cli

## Authentication / environment setup

Add to ~/.bashrc or ~/.zshrc:
```
export WOODPECKER_SERVER=https://woodpecker-ci.kevininscoe.com
export WOODPECKER_TOKEN=<your-api-token>
```

Get your token from the Woodpecker UI:
  Avatar menu (top-right) → User Settings → API Token

Or configure interactively:
```
woodpecker-cli setup --server https://woodpecker-ci.kevininscoe.com --token <token>
```

Test connection:
```
woodpecker-cli info
```

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://woodpecker-ci.org/docs/cli

## Command options

### Global flags (work with any subcommand)

```
--server, -s        Server address
--token, -t         Auth token (prefer env var WOODPECKER_TOKEN)
--config, -c        Path to config file
--log-level         Logging level (default: info)
--log-file          Log output destination
--pretty            Pretty-print debug output (default: true)
--nocolor           Disable colored output
--skip-verify       Skip SSL certificate verification
--socks-proxy       SOCKS proxy address
--disable-update-check  Disable update check
```

### pipeline — manage pipelines

```
woodpecker-cli pipeline ls <repo>          # list pipeline history
woodpecker-cli pipeline last <repo>        # show latest pipeline
woodpecker-cli pipeline show <repo> <id>   # show pipeline details
woodpecker-cli pipeline ps <repo> <id>     # show pipeline steps
woodpecker-cli pipeline start <repo> <id>  # restart a pipeline
woodpecker-cli pipeline stop <repo> <id>   # stop a pipeline
woodpecker-cli pipeline create <repo>      # trigger a new pipeline
woodpecker-cli pipeline deploy <repo>      # trigger deployment event
woodpecker-cli pipeline approve <repo> <id>
woodpecker-cli pipeline decline <repo> <id>
woodpecker-cli pipeline queue              # show queued pipelines
woodpecker-cli pipeline log show <repo> <id> <step>
woodpecker-cli pipeline log purge <repo> <id>
```

### repo — manage repositories

```
woodpecker-cli repo ls                     # list all repos
woodpecker-cli repo add <repo>             # enable a repo
woodpecker-cli repo rm <repo>              # disable a repo
woodpecker-cli repo show <repo>
woodpecker-cli repo sync <repo>            # sync repo metadata from forge
woodpecker-cli repo update <repo>
woodpecker-cli repo repair <repo>          # fix broken webhooks
woodpecker-cli repo chown <repo>           # reassign ownership
woodpecker-cli repo cron ls/add/rm <repo>  # manage cron jobs
woodpecker-cli repo secret ls/add/rm/show/update <repo>
woodpecker-cli repo registry ls/add/rm/show/update <repo>
```

### org — manage organizations

```
woodpecker-cli org ls
woodpecker-cli org secret ls/add/rm/show/update <org>
woodpecker-cli org registry ls/add/rm/show/update <org>
```

### admin — server administration

```
woodpecker-cli admin user ls/add/rm/show
woodpecker-cli admin org ls
woodpecker-cli admin secret ls/add/rm/show/update
woodpecker-cli admin registry ls/add/rm/show/update
woodpecker-cli admin log-level            # get or set server log level
```

### Other commands

```
woodpecker-cli lint [file]                 # validate .woodpecker.yml
  --strict                                 # treat warnings as errors
woodpecker-cli exec                        # run pipeline locally
woodpecker-cli info                        # show current user info
woodpecker-cli context ls                  # list saved contexts
woodpecker-cli context use <name>          # switch context
woodpecker-cli update                      # update CLI binary
```
